com.biomatters.geneious.publicapi.utilities

Class Interval

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.biomatters.geneious.publicapi.utilities.Interval
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    XMLSerializable, XMLSerializable.OldVersionCompatible, Iterable<Integer>

    public final class Interval
extends Object
implements Iterable<Integer>, XMLSerializable, XMLSerializable.OldVersionCompatible
    Represents a directional interval. This class is immutable.

    Zero-length intervals can be represented by this class - these are often used by Geneious to, for example, represent the position between two residues in a sequence. For example, new Interval(0, 0) represents the position before the first residue in a linear sequence (or the origin, in a circular sequence). On the other hand, new Interval(1, 1) represents the position between residues 0 and 1.

      • toXML

        public org.jdom.Element toXML()
        Description copied from interface: XMLSerializable
        Convert object to a JDOM element. The representation should be complete so that XMLSerializable.fromXML(org.jdom.Element) can completely restore the objects representation.

        It is recommended that the returned element use XMLSerializable.ROOT_ELEMENT_NAME as its name, in which case it must not define an attribute called "type". In this case, fromXML, will be called with an element whose name may differ from the element return from this function. This recommendation allows a more compact representation of the XML can be stored.

        This method generally should not be called directly. Instead, you should usually call XMLSerializer.classToXML(String, XMLSerializable) which calls this method internally.

        PluginDocument implementations of this method may choose to throw an XMLSerializationException, enclosed in a RuntimeException.

        Specified by:
        toXML in interface XMLSerializable
        Returns:
        object encoded as a JDOM element

        Description copied from interface: XMLSerializable.OldVersionCompatible
        Serializes this class to XML format, potentially to a format readable by an earlier version of Geneious. It is acceptable for the XML to include unnecessary tags that will be ignored by the earlier version. For example if the implementation has only extended the XML since the earlier version, then the XML returned may be identical to the XML returned for the current version.

        See XMLSerializable.toXML() for a more detailed description of what it means to serialize to XML.

        All classes that implement this method must also implement XMLSerializable.toXML() and should delegate back to this method using Geneious.getMajorVersion() and ProgressListener.EMPTY as parameters.

        Specified by:

        Description copied from interface: XMLSerializable
        Restore the object from the JDOM Element returned by XMLSerializable.toXML().

      • getComplement

        public List<Interval> getComplement(Interval otherIntervalContainedWithinThis)
        Parameters:
        otherIntervalContainedWithinThis - another interval, for which this.contains(otherIntervalContainedWithinThis) must be true.
        Returns:
        a list of either zero, one or two intervals constituting the complement of otherIntervalContainedWithinThis, within this Interval. All intervals in the returned list will be directed in the same direction as this. If and only if otherIntervalContainedWithinThis is equal to this, will the returned list be empty.

        Note: all empty intervals (any where from=toExclusive) are treated as the empty set, {}. Thus, the complement of the empty set within this interval will be (a copy of) this interval.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if otherIntervalContainedWithinThis was not contained by this.
        Since:
        API 4.604 (Geneious 6.0.4)

      • getIntersectionWith

        public Interval getIntersectionWith(Interval other)
        Parameters:
        other - the other interval to get the intersection of with this.
        Returns:
        an interval giving the intersection between this and other. There are three special cases to consider:
        • If the two intervals do not intersect but are both non-zero, returns null
        • If one or both of the intervals are the empty interval, returns null, unless:
        • If one of the intervals is empty, but the other "contains" that empty interval (see contains(Interval), then this returns a copy of the empty interval.
        Note that for the last point, the returned interval is still technically an "empty" interval, so the set-theoretic meaning of contains is not violated. It is simply that there are two representations of an empty intersection, null being the other.
        Since:
        API 4.604 (Geneious 6.0.4)

      • merge

        public static List<Interval> merge(List<Interval> _intervals)
        Merges a list of intervals, i.e. replaces sets of overlapping or directly adjacent intervals with a single interval.

        Empty intervals are preserved (unless they are contained within other intervals).

        Each result interval will only be directed left if all intervals contributing to that result interval were directed left

        Parameters:
        _intervals -
        Returns:
        Merged set of intervals, ordered from left to right (increasing coordinates)

      • getIntersection

        Returns a (merged) list of the intersecting intervals between groups of annotations. For example if there group 1 is [0,10), [20,30) and group 2 is [3,22) then the result will be [3,10), [20,22).
        Parameters:

        Returns:

      • clipToRange

        public Interval clipToRange(int minIndexInclusive,
                   int maxIndexExclusive)
        Clips the ends of this interval so that it does not extend outside the range [minIndexInclusive,maxIndexExclusive).

        If this interval lies entirely outside the given range or if it is a 0 length interval outside the given range, it is clipped to a 0-length interval on the closest side of [minIndexInclusive,maxIndexExclusive).

        If minIndexInclusive == maxIndexExclusive, this method always returns a 0 length interval corresponding to that range no matter what this interval already is.

        Parameters:
        minIndexInclusive -
        maxIndexExclusive -
        Returns:
        a clipped interval, or this interval if it doesn't need to be clipped.
